   343	
   344	## 7. Determinism & Parity with Reference
   345	
   346	### 7.1 Fixed-Point Determination
   347	
   348	The `optimalLinearFixedPoint` function implements a **deterministic least-squares fit**. Given the same input array, it should produce the same fixed point as:
   349	- pynumpress (Python reference)
   350	- numpress-rs (Rust reference)
   351	
   352	**Why deterministic:**
   353	- Linear algebra: least-squares solution is unique (assuming full rank, which it is for typical m/z).
   354	- No randomization: the algorithm is purely algebraic.
   355	
   356	### 7.2 Byte Identity
   357	
   358	Once the fixed point is determined, the encoding is **byte-deterministic**:
   359	- 5-byte ints are packed identically.
   360	- 4-bit half-bytes are packed identically.
   361	- No branching based on data; only data-driven residuals.
   362	
   363	**Test:** Compare `encode(m/z_from_small.RAW)` from our C# vs. pynumpress for a subset of m/z values. Should be identical.
   364	
   365	### 7.3 Round-Trip Accuracy
   366	
   367	- **Pynumpress:** Guarantees reversibility; decode(encode(x)) ≈ x within 0.002 ppm.
   368	- **Our C# port:** Should achieve the same by mirroring the algorithm exactly.
   369	
   370	**L∞ error bound:** ~2e−5 per value (empirically validated by pynumpress test suite).
   371	
   372	---
   373	
   374	## 8. Decision: Vendor vs. External Dependency
   375	
   376	### 8.1 Recommended Decision: Vendor as Source File
   377	
   378	| Criterion | Verdict |
   379	|-----------|---------|
   380	| **License compatibility** | ✓ Apache-2.0 compatible with MIT |
   381	| **Size & complexity** | ✓ ~200 lines, no external deps |
   382	| **Maintainability** | ✓ Minimal; algorithm is stable (ISO standard-like) |
   383	| **Performance** | ✓ Pure managed code, inlining friendly |
   384	| **AnyCPU native arm64** | ✓ No platform-specific code |
   385	| **Vendorability** | ✓ Self-contained source file |
   386	
   387	### 8.2 Rationale
   388	
   389	- **Hand-port from C++:** The ms-numpress C++ source is ~400 lines, well-commented, and published. Porting ~150 lines of the core encode/decode logic to C# is straightforward and introduces no external runtime dependency.
   390	- **Avoid NuGet:** No official C# NuGet package exists. A hypothetical numpress-rs via FFI would add complexity (P/Invoke, native library management).
   391	- **Avoid x64 markers:** mzLib (historical) and other .NET ports carry x64-specific baggage. Our hand-port is pure managed C# (AnyCPU).
   392	
   393	---
   394	
   395	## 9. Verification Checklist
   396	
   397	- [ ] Hand-port MSNumpress.cs from the canonical C++ source.
   398	- [ ] Unit tests: round-trip on synthetic m/z arrays.
   399	- [ ] Cross-check: encode with C#, decode with pynumpress (subprocess call in test).
   400	- [ ] Byte identity: Compare encoded bytes from C# vs. pynumpress on the same fixed point.
   401	- [ ] Read small.numpress.mzpeak metadata; extract m/z bytes; decode with C# and verify L∞ error < 2e-5.
   402	- [ ] Build + test native arm64 (dotnet run -c Release).
   403	- [ ] Verify no x64 markers in the assembly (use `file` or `dotnet --info`).
   404	
   405	---
   406	
   407	## 10. References
   408	
   409	**Primary sources:**
   410	1. **ms-numpress GitHub:** https://github.com/ms-numpress/ms-numpress
   411	   - C++ reference: `cpp/MSNumpress.cpp`, `cpp/MSNumpress.h`
   412	   - License: Apache-2.0
   413	   
   414	2. **pynumpress:** `python3.11 -c "import pynumpress; help(pynumpress.encode_linear)"`
   415	   - Wrapper around C++ via Cython
   416	   - Provides `encode_linear`, `decode_linear`, `optimal_linear_fixed_point`
   417	   
   418	3. **numpress-rs:** https://github.com/mzdata/numpress-rs (used by mzdata Rust library)
   419	   - Pure Rust port of ms-numpress
   420	   - MIT license

